{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_19","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"mkdir -p .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions\ncat > .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions/minimal_native_direction.md <<'EOF'\n# Design Direction: minimal_native_direction\n## Target Emotion\n- First 10 seconds: calm control, not hype; user should feel “I know where to start right now.”\n- Wake state: focused urgency with low cognitive load; one obvious next action and no decorative distractions.\n- After task completion: grounded progress and relief; clear acknowledgment plus immediate recovery/next-step option.\n\n## Visual Principles\n- Layout density: medium-compact in setup screens, compact in wake-active screens; keep mission-critical content above the fold.\n- Contrast model: neutral surfaces with one semantic accent per screen state; avoid multi-accent competition.\n- Shape language: native rounded rectangles and SF Symbols; no novelty containers.\n- Information hierarchy: one primary CTA, one state headline, one secondary explanation; tertiary actions in menus/sheets.\n- Empty-state tone: practical and instructive (“Set first wake task”) rather than motivational fluff.\n- Native iOS alignment: use standard tab bar, navigation bar titles, list/grouped sections, system sheet patterns, and default gesture expectations.\n\n## Colors And Tokens\n- Semantic tokens: \"'`color.bg.primary`, `color.bg.grouped`, `color.text.primary`, `color.text.secondary`, `color.action.primary`, `color.state.success`, `color.state.warning`, `color.state.destructive`, `color.state.disabled`, `color.border.subtle`.\n- Light mode: near-system neutrals (`bg.primary` very light, text high-contrast dark), accent used only for active mission actions.\n- Dark mode: true dark grouped surfaces with preserved text contrast; avoid glowing saturated backgrounds during wake state.\n- Accent strategy: single accent family for wake action (blue/teal range) and never reuse destructive red as motivational color.\n- Destructive states: red reserved for irreversible actions and mission failure confirmations.\n- Success states: green used for completion confirmation and streak-repair success only.\n- Disabled states: opacity + contrast-safe text fallback; never rely on alpha alone.\n- High-contrast fallback: force WCAG-safe pairings, remove subtle borders, increase divider/label contrast and icon stroke weight.\n\n## Typography\n- Dynamic Type: all body and controls scale with system text settings; no clipped fixed-height CTA rows.\n- Roles: large title for screen intent, title3/headline for active state label, body for instructions, footnote/caption for caveats.\n- Numeric treatment: monospaced digits for timers/streak counts to prevent layout jitter.\n- Minimum readable sizes: body never below 17pt equivalent, secondary metadata never below 13pt equivalent.\n\n## Motion\n- Transition principles: short, directional transitions that confirm state change (setup -> active -> completion), not decorative choreography.\n- Reduce Motion: replace movement with opacity/state swaps and static progress updates.\n- Haptics: light impact on primary wake action tap, success notification on completion, warning notification on miss.\n- Timing ranges: 120-180ms micro transitions, 220-320ms screen transitions, no looping animations in active wake mode.\n- Wake-state restraint: no bouncing counters, no celebratory bursts, no pulsing urgency loops.\n\n## Screen-By-Screen Implications\n- Onboarding: keep existing deterministic sequence but add explicit skip-safe path and “you can adjust later” defaults.\n- Home: reframe as “today readiness” with a single top mission card, then secondary cards (history/profile links) below.\n- Primary list: prioritize due/next wake tasks first, collapse low-priority metadata into disclosure rows.\n- Create/edit: progressive disclosure order: intent -> schedule -> strictness; advanced options hidden under expandable section.\n- Active task: one dominant CTA, current-state banner, explicit fallback/retry action; suppress non-essential navigation prompts.\n- Completion: immediate confirmation, short summary of what was completed, one recovery path if partially failed.\n- History/streaks: explain streak changes in plain language (“missed due to X, repair by Y”), not only raw counts.\n- Profile/settings: separate mission operations from legal/account danger actions with distinct grouped sections.\n- Paywall/subscription: present after value moment (post-completion/history), not during active wake flow.\n\n## Monetization Implications\n- Premium promise this supports: higher reliability controls (advanced wake checks, deeper history insights, customization) while core wake execution remains stable.\n- Free should include: onboarding, basic wake task creation, active wake flow, completion logging, basic history.\n- Avoid dark patterns: no countdown pressure on paywall, no blocked dismiss in wake-critical contexts, no shaming copy after misses.\n\n## Accessibility Risks\n- VoiceOver: risk of weak announcement order in dense wake cards; require explicit rotor-friendly grouping.\n- Dynamic Type: compact active layouts may truncate timer/state labels; require multiline-safe containers.\n- Contrast: neutral minimal palette can under-shoot in low-light dark mode if separators are too subtle.\n- Reduced motion: must avoid hidden meaning in motion-only state changes.\n- Haptics-only feedback: never rely on haptics without textual/visual confirmation.\n- Cognitive load: minimal styling can still overload if too many secondary metrics appear at wake moment.\n- One-handed use: top-heavy primary actions can hurt reachability on large iPhones.\n\n## Implementation Risks\n- SwiftUI complexity: state-driven minimal UI is simple, but strict semantic state mapping across wake phases can drift.\n- Custom component risk: low if we stay with system lists/cards; rises if custom wake timer controls are introduced.\n- Animation risk: low if we keep system transitions; moderate if syncing timer, haptics, and banners manually.\n- App Store risk: low-medium; coercive subscription placement during wake flows would raise review risk.\n- Localization risk: concise minimal copy can become ambiguous in translated strings; needs explicit context keys.\n- Scope tradeoffs: biggest win is hierarchy/state clarity, not full visual redesign; avoid broad design-system rewrite.\n\n## Source List\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md` - baseline IA, flow shape, and current weaknesses.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md` - consolidated cross-source opportunities and anti-patterns.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md` - pattern-level guidance for onboarding/home/active/profile.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md` - progressive disclosure and single-action urgent-mode pattern evidence.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md` - source-limited fallback principles for calm setup and recovery.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md` - accessibility/discoverability/interruption-safe constraints.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md` - calm setup vs urgent wake tone separation.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md` - evidence-gap constraints and conservative assumptions.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json` - confirms earlier evidence gaps and need for cautious inference.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json` - network/tooling constraints affecting evidence confidence.\n\n## What To Adapt\n- Progressive onboarding with reversible defaults and explicit skip-safe messaging.\n- Single dominant wake action with explicit next-state communication.\n- Recovery-first completion and streak repair explanations.\n- Strict separation of mission-critical controls from account/legal actions.\n- Native iOS component usage to reduce implementation and accessibility risk.\n\n## What Not To Copy\n- Any competitor or pattern-library exact layouts, copy, icon sets, spacing systems, or animation signatures.\n- Proprietary Mobbin/PageFlows compositions or branded task-reward visuals.\n- Punitive/shame framing, forced paywall interruptions, or high-pressure countdown monetization.\n- Hidden timers or implicit transitions that require guessing the current wake state.\n\n## No Secret Output\n- No credentials, tokens, cookies, keys, signed URLs, or private account data were used or reproduced.\nEOF\n\nsed -n '\"'1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions/minimal_native_direction.md\"","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
